LINUX EXAM QUICK REFERENCE GUIDE
================================

GENERAL MENTAL MODEL
--------------------
Most commands follow this pattern:

command [options] input | next_command > output_file

command  = action
options  = modify behavior (-i, -C, etc)
input    = files or text
|         = pipe output into another command
>         = save output (overwrite)
>>        = append output


BASIC NAVIGATION
----------------
Show current location:
pwd

List files:
ls

Go to folder:
cd path/to/folder

Go home:
cd ~


FILE CREATION
-------------
Create empty file:
touch filename.txt

Create file from command output:
command > filename.txt


REDIRECTION
-----------
Overwrite output:
>

Append output:
>>

Example:
command > output.txt
command >> output.txt


PIPING (|)
----------
Pipe sends output into next command.

Example:
command1 | command2

Common use:
grep "word" file.txt | less


MAN PAGES (MANUALS)
-------------------
View manual:
man command

Save manual to file:
man command > output.txt

Append multiple manuals:
man cmd1 > output.txt
man cmd2 >> output.txt

Better formatting:
man command | col -b > output.txt


GREP BASICS
-----------
Search for text:
grep "word" file.txt

Search multiple files:
grep "word" *.txt

Ignore case:
grep -i "word" file.txt

Show filename in results:
grep -H "word" *.txt


GREP CONTEXT (ASSOCIATED INFORMATION)
-------------------------------------
Lines before + after match:
grep -C 3 "word" file.txt

Only before:
grep -B 3 "word" file.txt

Only after:
grep -A 3 "word" file.txt

Common exam pattern:
grep -i -H -C 3 "word" *.txt > output.txt


IMPORTANT GREP RULE
-------------------
Never include output file in input wildcard.

BAD:
grep "word" *.txt > output.txt
(if output.txt matches *.txt)

GOOD:
grep "word" notes*.txt > output.txt


REGEX / EXTRACT MATCHES
-----------------------
Extract only matching text:
grep -Eo "pattern" file.txt

Extract URLs:
grep -Eo 'https?://[^ ]+' file.txt


PIPE TO OPEN URL
----------------
Extract link and open browser:
grep -Eo 'https?://[^ ]+' file.txt | head -n 1 | xargs qutebrowser


USER MANAGEMENT
---------------
Create new user:
sudo useradd -m username

Set password:
sudo passwd username

List all users:
cat /etc/passwd

List usernames only:
cut -d: -f1 /etc/passwd > users.txt


LIST USERS + SAVE TO FILE
-------------------------
cut -d: -f1 /etc/passwd > winners.txt


COMMON FILE COMMANDS
--------------------
Copy file:
cp source.txt destination.txt

Move file:
mv file.txt folder/

Remove file:
rm file.txt


VIEW FILE CONTENT
-----------------
Show file:
cat file.txt

Scroll file:
less file.txt

Show first lines:
head file.txt

Show last lines:
tail file.txt


PERMISSIONS / GROUP FIXES
-------------------------
Add user to group:
sudo usermod -aG groupname username

Check groups:
groups


SYMBOLIC LINKS (SHORTCUTS)
--------------------------
Create link:
ln -s /real/path ~/shortcut

Remove link:
rm ~/shortcut


EXAM WORKFLOW (SAFE ROUTINE)
----------------------------
1. Go to correct folder:
   cd path/to/files

2. Confirm files exist:
   ls

3. Run command

4. Verify output:
   cat output.txt

5. Submit output file


FAST TROUBLESHOOT CHECKLIST
---------------------------
If command doesn't work:
- run pwd
- run ls
- check spelling (case-sensitive)
- simplify command

If grep shows nothing:
- try -i
- check file with cat
- test simple search first

If "input file is also output":
- output file included in wildcard
- specify exact input files


CORE EXAM CONCEPTS
------------------
grep   = search text
|      = pass output to next command
>      = save output
>>     = add to file
man    = manuals
cat    = display file
cut    = extract columns
xargs  = send input as command argument

END QUICK REFERENCE
